                  <persName id="t18321018-82-person802">
                  THOMAS 
                  STOTHARD
               <interp inst="t18321018-82-person802" type="surname" value="STOTHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-82-person802" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-82-person802" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am <rs id="t18321018-82-viclabel464" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18321018-82-victim801 t18321018-82-viclabel464"></join> to Mr. Newdigate. On the 7th of October the prisoner came to his door, begging; I said the family were gone to church, and there was not any body at home to give him any thing - I went to the stable, and was gone about ten minutes; as I returned, Little had a pair of shoes - one was in his pocket, and the other he was putting in; one was mine, and the other one of my fellow-servant's - Smith stood by the side of him, and could see what he was doing.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18321018-82-person803">
                  JAMES 
                  DARVELL
               <interp inst="t18321018-82-person803" type="surname" value="DARVELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-82-person803" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-82-person803" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a headborough. I went with Birch to take the prisoners - Smith said he was sure one was as bad as the other, for he took one shoe and Little took the other, and when he saw the servant coming, he gave the shoe to Little to hide, for he had no where to hide it; and Little said that was the fact.</p>

               <p>
            
